servings: 2
author: Lily Stevens
time required: 40 minutes
---

Preheat your #oven{} to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7.

Drain the @Halloumi{225%g}, then cut it into 2 slices per person. Place the slices into a #medium bowl{} of cold water and leave to soak.

While the halloumi soaks, chop the @Potatoes{450%g} lengthways into 1cm slices, then chop into 1cm wide chips (no need to peel).

Pop the chips onto a #large baking tray{}. Drizzle with @oil{}, sprinkle over the @Black Sesame Seeds{5} and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Toss to coat. Spread out in a single layer.

> TIP: Use two baking trays if necessary.

When the #oven{} is hot, bake on the top shelf until golden, ~{25-30%minutes}. Turn halfway through.

Meanwhile, halve the @Burger Buns{2}.

Thinly slice the @Medium Tomato{1}.

About ~{10%minutes} before the chips are ready, remove the halloumi slices from the cold water, pop them onto a #plate{} lined with #kitchen paper{} and pat them dry.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a #large frying pan{} on medium-high heat.

Once hot, add the halloumi and fry until golden, ~{2-3%minutes} each side.

Remove the #pan{} from the heat and add the @Gochujang Paste{30%g} and @Honey{15%g}.

> TIP: If your honey has hardened, pop it in a #bowl{} of hot water for 1 min.

Turn the halloumi in the sauce until nicely coated and sticky, ~{1%minute}.

Pop the burger buns onto a #baking tray{} and into the oven to warm through, ~{2-3%minutes}.

When everything's ready, spread the @Mayonnaise{2%tbsp} over the bun bases. Top with the glazed halloumi and sliced tomato, then top with a handful of @Wild Rocket{40%g}. Spoon over any remaining gochujang glaze. Sandwich shut with the bun lids.

Transfer the burgers to your plates and serve the sesame chips and remaining rocket alongside.

Drizzle the @Balsamic Glaze{12%ml} over the rocket to finish.

Enjoy!